	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104214279432047><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=14379&mid=104214279432047>RE: Price</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=14379&mid=104214279432047#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=113552><span id=Scholar>Alikaar</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>66 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jan 9th 3:33 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.80]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Demand determines price.&nbsp;&nbsp;Not &quot;overhead&quot;.  Not &quot;time invested in developing skill.&quot;  Not how many or how difficult a specific mob-dropped item is to acquire.<br><br>The sole determining factor in setting a price for any item, skill-crafted or otherwise, is how much the person paying for it is willing to spend.<br><br>If YOU believe that a person wants too much for an item, DON'T buy it.  If they are &quot;gougeing', then they will be forced to lower their price.  If they aren't, then SOMEONE ELSE will get the item.  Maybe then YOU can invest your time and effort raising your tailoring (or whatever) skill to the appropriate level, kill the required quantity of the appropriate mobs and make the item for yourself.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>--Alikaar of Tarrew Mar<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
